<title> Pitch token </title>

<h1> Pitch token </h1>

<subsection>

<p> Abjad notes and chords accept all of the following as pitch input:

<ul>
   <li> Python <tt>int</tt> and <tt>long</tt> instances
   <li> Python <tt>float</tt> instances
   <li> Abjad <code>Pitch</code> instances
</ul>

<p> For example:

<abjad>
   abjad> note = Note(0, (1, 4))
   hide> measure = Measure((1, 4), [note])
   hide> measure.meter.transparent = True
   hide> show(measure)
</abjad>

<p> And:

<abjad>
   abjad> note = Note(5.5, (1, 4))
   hide> measure = Measure((1, 4), [note])
   hide> measure.meter.transparent = True
   hide> show(measure)
</abjad>

<p> And:

<abjad>
   abjad> note = Note(Pitch(13), (1, 4))
   hide> measure = Measure((1, 4), [note])
   hide> measure.meter.transparent = True
   hide> show(measure)
</abjad>

<p> The Abjad <strong>pitch token</strong> generalizes these four types of input.

<p> Examples in the documentation that ask for valid pitch token input accept any of the types of input show here.

</subsection>

<comments>

<p> Abjad accepts only those <code>float</code> instances evenly divisible by <tt>0.5</tt> as valid pitch token instances because Abjad implements accidental drawing symbols to the level of the quartertone only.

</comments>
